            "content": "The Problem: A Tucson homeowner with a 1985-built home (38 years old, original copper plumbing, never had water softener) experienced their first pinhole leak under their kitchen sink—a tiny spray of water from a cold water pipe. We repaired it for $320. Four months later, they had another pinhole in their master bathroom wall—another $480 repair. Three months after that, a third pinhole appeared in their laundry room. At this point, they had spent $1,350 on three pinhole repairs in 7 months, and we explained the hard truth: their entire copper plumbing system was corroding from the inside due to Tucson's hard water, and more pinholes would continue appearing unpredictably."
